content.description: A tricky start off the ground and straight up to the anchor!
content.protection: Top rope. Some creativity will help in getting to the top of rock to build an anchor. Fifty feet of static rope or webbing should be enough to build a good two point anchor.
content.location: Backside of Tree Wall pillar. Center of wall between Rickamortis 5.7 and Archangel Arete 5.6R.

content.description: Rickamortis is a superb route for the area that includes a no hands rest on highly featured rock.
content.protection: Top rope. Some creativity will help in finding a way up the rock to build a top rope anchor. Fifty feet of static rope or webbing should be enough to build a good two point anchor.
content.location: Backside of the Tree Wall pillar. As of now, the bottom of the route is vandalized with graffiti. See pictures for topo.

content.description: Climb the arete and have fun, but a fall can result in a nasty swing into the buttress that Rickamortis 5.7 follows. When near the top, traverse left and then straight up to the anchor. Route includes a hold that looks like a hand squeezed the rock to shape.
content.protection: Top rope. Some creativity will help in finding a way to the top of rock to build an anchor. Fifty feet of static rope or webbing should be enough to build a good two point anchor.
content.location: Arete to the right of Sandbagged 5.9. Backside of the Tree Wall pillar.

content.description: Rock will be on the right side if hiking downhill from the fire tower. There’s a tree growing along the uphill side that has grown very close to the rock. Three good climbs can be found around the backside which can be identified by some spray paint at the bottom of route.
